[[File:PathtoTruth.png|thumb|right|200px|''[[Jedi Quest: Path to Truth]]'', the series' introductory story]]
'''''Star Wars: Jedi Quest''''' is a series of young-reader novels written by [[Jude Watson]] and published by [[Scholastic]]. A follow-up to the [[Star Wars: Jedi Apprentice|''Jedi Apprentice'']] series, the series follows [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] and his master [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] between [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''Star Wars'': Episode I ''The Phantom Menace'']] and [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']] and on the back of the book, above each story's synopsis, it says "Obi-Wan Kenobi & Anakin Skywalker. Master and Apprentice. Chosen by fate. Destined for Conflict."

While originally scheduled to be a full line of toys and a multimedia event like ''[[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire]]'' and [[Star Wars: Clone Wars|''Clone Wars'']], Jedi Quest was reduced to a series of novels [[Star Wars: Jedi Quest (comic series)|and comics]] along with a couple of leftover action figures released from 2000 to 2001.<ref name="ERC">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]''</ref> While the series includes eleven titles and two special editions, the introductory novel, ''Path to Truth'', is unnumbered, leaving the last ten books of the eleven-book series numbered 1–10. The series was succeeded by the ''[[Star Wars: The Last of the Jedi|Last of the Jedi]]'' series which starred ''Jedi Quest'' supporting character [[Ferus Olin]] as the protagonist.

==Development==
The hardcover release launched a new young reader book series focused on [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker’s]] early teen [[Standard year/Legends|years]] apprenticed to [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]]. In [[2000]], the publishing and product development teams at [[Lucas Licensing]] first planned the ''Jedi Quest'' banner to encompass books, comics, toys and roleplaying games. An internal [[Lucasfilm]] memo dated March 13, 2000, described six possible action figures from [[Hasbro]]: a “full body tattoo [[Darth Maul/Legends|Darth Maul]],” Obi-Wan in [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] training outfit, Anakin Skywalker in cold-weather gear, the [[Pirate/Legends|pirate]] [[Krayn]], a [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiee]] pirate, and “a possible prototype [[Battle droid/Legends|battle droid]].” The memo also listed two [[Micro Machines Star Wars Action Fleet|Action Fleet vehicles]] for the ''[[Micro Machines]]'' line (though it did not elaborate on their type), a roleplaying book from [[Wizards of the Coast]] for October [[2001]], a six-part [[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse]] comic series, and tentative plans for an online interactive comic (possibly included as a CD-ROM with the action figures), as well as an audio drama.

The ''Jedi Quest'' multimedia project ultimately did not come to full fruition, though the [[Scholastic]] young reader series proved popular enough to carry on without any ancillary product support. Dark Horse only adapted the first book, [[Jedi Quest: Path to Truth|''Path to Truth'']], as a four-part [[Star Wars: Jedi Quest (comic series)|''Jedi Quest'' series]] by writer [[Ryder Windham]] and artist [[Pop Mhan]] in 2001. That year, Hasbro did release several [[Star Wars Legends|Expended Universe ''Star Wars'']] action figures – the shirtless Darth Maul; training gear [[Qui-Gon Jinn/Legends|Qui-Gon Jinn]], Obi-Wan Kenobi, and Darth Maul; and a [[Obi-Wan Kenobi's cold weather suit|cold-weather gear Obi-Wan]] – but none bore any mention of the ''Jedi Quest'' series. Hasbro did use the ''Jedi Quest'' name for a [[Star Wars Jedi Quest Kids Club|Kids Club]], an online promotion for kids aged four through twelve that included a short-lived [[Star Wars Jedi Quest Kids Club Magazine|magazine]] spotlighting [[Star Wars (Hasbro toy line)|Hasbro ''Star Wars'' toys]]. The roleplaying, interactive, and audio tie-ins never materialized.

The ''Jedi Quest'' series was also meant to offer glimpses of [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|Episode II]], but only ''Path to Truth'' arrived in advance of the [[2002]] Episode II tie-in titles. The [[Insectoid/Legends|insectoid]] [[Colicoid/Legends|Colicoid]] [[Alien/Legends|aliens]] featured in the book were at one point planned to be the first appearance of [[Geonosian/Legends|Geonosian]] aliens prior to the ''Attack of the Clones''.<ref name="ERC" />

==Continuity==
The adventures experienced by Kenobi and Skywalker in the ten-year gap between Episodes I and II ([[32 BBY/Legends|32]]-[[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]]) are alluded to in the Episode II ''novelization'' by [[R. A. Salvatore]], [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones (novelization)|''Attack of the Clones'']], when Jedi protector Anakin Skywalker has escorted [[Senator/Legends|Senator]] Padmé Amidala back to [[Naboo/Legends|Naboo]] after two [[Plot to assassinate Senator Amidala/Legends|assassination attempts]] on her life in the [[Galactic City/Legends|galactic capital]] of [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]].

Retiring to the seclusion of the [[Naberrie family/Legends|Naberrie family's]] island retreat of [[Varykino/Legends|Varykino]] in the remote [[Lake Country/Legends|Lake Country]] of Naboo, Anakin and Padmé, after an enjoyable meadow excursion, meet at dusk on the lodge's dining terrace that looks out over the lake for their evening meal. It is then, after the pair has settled in at the table, that Skywalker begins "recounting some of the adventures he had known over the last ten years, training and flying with Obi-Wan."<ref name="SW:AOTC">[[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones (novelization)|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'' novelization]]</ref>

The working title for ''Secrets of the Jedi'' was ''Jedi Quest Special Edition''.

